6 Sec. 173. (1) The commission shall establish a distributed
7 generation program by order issued by July 19, 2017. The commission
8 may promulgate rules the commission considers necessary to
9 implement this program. Any rules adopted regarding time limits for
10 approval of parallel operation must recognize grid reliability and
11 safety complications including those arising from equipment
12 saturation, use of multiple technologies, and proximity to
13 synchronous motor loads. The program must apply to all electric
14 utilities whose rates are regulated by the commission and
15 alternative electric suppliers in this state.
16 (2) Except as otherwise provided under this part, an electric
17 customer of any class is eligible to interconnect an eligible
18 electric generator with the customer's local electric utility and
19 operate the eligible electric generator in parallel with the
20 distribution system. The program must limit each customer to
21 generation capacity designed to meet up to 110% 100% of the
22 customer's electricity consumption for the previous 12 months. The
23 commission may waive the application, interconnection, and
24 installation requirements of this part for customers participating
25 in the net metering program under the commission's March 29, 2005
26 order in case no. U-14346.
27 (3) An electric utility or alternative electric supplier is
28 not required to allow for a distributed generation program that is
29 greater than 10% 1% of its average in-state peak load for the
RMH H02431'25 (H-3) cxb0i8

21
1 preceding 5 calendar years. The electric utility or alternative
2 electric supplier shall notify the commission if its distributed
3 generation program reaches the 10% 1% limit under this subsection.
4 The 10% 1% limit under this subsection shall be allocated as
5 follows:
6 (a) Not less than 50% for customers with an eligible electric
7 generator capable of generating 20 kilowatts or less.
8 (b) Not more than 50% for customers with an eligible electric
9 generator capable of generating more than 20 kilowatts but not more
10 than 550 kilowatts.
11 (4) Selection of customers for participation in the
12 distributed generation program must be based on the order in which
13 the applications for participation in the program are received by
14 the electric utility or alternative electric supplier.
15 (5) An electric utility or alternative electric supplier shall
16 not discontinue or refuse to provide electric service to a customer
17 solely because the customer participates in the distributed
18 generation program. An electric utility or alternative electric
19 supplier shall not limit the rate schedule under which a customer
20 is served solely because the customer participates in the
21 distributed generation program.
22 (6) The distributed generation program created under
23 subsection (1) must include all of the following:
24 (a) Statewide uniform interconnection requirements for all
25 eligible electric generators. The interconnection requirements must
26 be designed to protect electric utility workers and equipment and
27 the general public.
28 (b) Distributed generation equipment and its installation
29 shall meet all current local and state electric and construction
RMH H02431'25 (H-3) cxb0i8

22
1 code requirements. Any equipment that is certified by a nationally
2 recognized testing laboratory to IEEE 1547.1-2020 testing standards
3 and in compliance with UL 1741 scope 1.1A and installed in
4 compliance with this part is considered to be compliant. The
5 commission may adopt successor requirements by promulgating rules
6 under the administrative procedures act of 1969, 1969 PA 306, MCL
7 24.201 to 24.328, if the commission determines the successor
8 requirements are reasonable and consistent with the purposes of
9 this subdivision. Within the time provided by the commission in
10 rules promulgated under subsection (1) and consistent with good
11 utility practice, and the protection of electric utility workers,
12 electric utility equipment, and the general public, an electric
13 utility may study, confirm, and ensure that an eligible electric
14 generator installation at the customer's site meets the IEEE
15 1547.1-2020 requirements or any applicable successor requirements
16 adopted by the commission. If necessary to promote grid reliability
17 or safety, the commission may promulgate rules that require the use
18 of inverters that perform specific automated grid-balancing
19 functions to integrate distributed generation onto the electric
20 grid. Inverters that interconnect distributed generation resources
21 may be owned and operated by electric utilities. Both of the
22 following must be completed before the equipment is operated in
23 parallel with the distribution system of the utility:
24 (i) Utility testing and approval of the interconnection,
25 including all metering.
26 (ii) Execution of a parallel operating agreement.
27 (c) A uniform application form and process to be used by all
28 electric utilities and alternative electric suppliers in this
29 state. Customers who are served by an alternative electric supplier
RMH H02431'25 (H-3) cxb0i8

23
1 shall submit a copy of the application to the electric utility for
2 the customer's service area.
3 (d) Distributed generation customers shall pay the retail
4 rates for electricity inflow under the rate schedule under which
5 the customer is served.
6 (7) Distributed generation customers shall receive a monthly
7 bill credit for outflow as determined by the commission. Credits
8 for outflow must reflect cost of service.
9 (8) Each electric utility and alternative electric supplier
10 shall maintain records of all applications and up-to-date records
11 of all active eligible electric generators located within their
12 service area.
13 Sec. 191. (1) Subject to subsection (2), to To implement this
14 act, the commission shall issue orders or promulgate rules pursuant
15 to in accordance with the administrative procedures act of 1969,
16 1969 PA 306, MCL 24.201 to 24.328.
17 (2) By January 1, 2026, the commission shall issue an order
18 providing formats and guidelines for an electric provider to submit
19 a clean energy plan pursuant to section 51.
